<DOC><DOCNO> AP880801-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0731EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   08-01 0513</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0538</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's economy kept growing in July,although the pace slowed slightly from the previous month,according to a survey of corporate purchasing managers.   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which Sundayreleased its monthly survey of economic trends at more than 250industrial companies, said its index of economic growth dipped to59 percent in July from 59.3 percent in June.   A reading above 50 percent indicates the economy is expanding,while levels below that point generally indicate the economy iscontracting.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Grain and soybean futures have scored their first major advancein more than two weeks and many other commodity markets followedsuit, reversing a trend of generally falling prices.   But a surprising government report Friday showing the nation'scattle herd to be larger than many experts had predicted wasexpected to bring a sharp drop in cattle futures prices this week.   In another report, the Agriculture Department said that pricesfarmers got for raw products in July rose 3.6 percent from June asthe drought continued to take a toll on crop and livestockproduction.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Macmillan Inc., the target of a pair ofunsolicited takeover proposals, says its board has authorizedmanagement to evaluate the possibility of selling all or parts ofthe company and other options.   The publishing company said Friday the board gave thoseinstructions as it voted to oppose a tender offer from a group ledby Texas investor Robert M. Bass that values the company at $1.9billion. The board called the bid inadequate.   British entrepreneur Robert Maxwell has indicated he is preparedto offer about $2.06 billion for Macmillan under certain conditions.</TEXT><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Koppers Co. says its $660 million deal to sellits chemicals division to a management-led group has collapsed.   Friday's announcement came a day after sources said recentconcerns about the chemical segment's environmental liabilitieswere jeopardizing the agreement for British construction magnateBrian Beazer to sell the operations to managers and their outsidepartner.   The sale would have helped Beazer finance his $1.8 billionpurchase of Koppers.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The first big failure of a leveraged buyout hasfailed to stir the junk-bond market.   Analysts predicted Friday the bankruptcy filing by drugstorechain Revco D.S. Inc. would concern few holders of other high-riskcorporate bonds.   Revco is the only major company to seek protection from itscreditors after going private in a junk-bond financed buyout.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal government and the New York StockExchange say they are examining an apparently bogus claim of alarge investment in General Cinema Corp. that triggered a sharprise in the price of the company's stock.   Securities experts said Friday the filing by an unknown Londonman from a fictitious London address of a 6.1 percent stockacquisition in General Cinema raises questions about Securities andExchange Commission guidelines.   General Cinema received a brown manila envelope with no returnaddress and a New Jersey postmark.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>